titlestmt.titleproper: Register of the Milan Gavrilović Papers
titlestmt.author: Finding aid prepared by Ales Pokorny and Ronald Bulatoff

profiledesc.creation: This finding aid was produced using the Archivists' Toolkit 2016-02-11T11:38-0800

did.abstract: Correspondence, diaries, speeches and writings, memoranda, reports, notes, printed matter, and photographs, relating to Yugoslav politics and government, relations between Yugoslavia and the Soviet Union, Yugoslavia during World War II, the Yugoslav government-in-exile, Draza Mihailovic and the Cetnik resistance movement in occupied Yugoslavia, and the activities of Serbian émigré groups following World War II. Also available on microfilm (66 reels).

eventgrp.event: Receives elementary and secondary education in Eastern Serbia

chronitem.event: Enters Law School, University of Belgrade. Founds and edits the student paper Oslobodjenje. Works as a reporter for Dnevni List, a Belgrade daily
Suspended for a year from the University for refusing to attend classes as a political protest
During Easter vacation joins the chetniks to fight for the liberation of southern parts of Serbia. Wounded in the Battle of Čelopek
Graduates from Law School, University of Belgrade
Enters Law School, University of Paris

Receives Doctorate of Law degree (Doctorat d'Etat), University of Paris. His dissertation ("L'état et le droit") was awarded French state prize. Joins Political Section, Serbian Ministry of Foreign Affairs
Takes unofficial leave from the Ministry to fight in the Balkan War as a chetnik
Secretary to the Prime Minister and Minister of Foreign Affairs, Nikola Pašić
Married Jelena Cincar-Janković
Serves in London (1916), Athens (1918), Berlin (1922), and Rome (1923), resigning from the service with the rank of Counselor
Joins the newly founded Agrarian Party and is elected member of its Executive Committee
Vice President, Serbian Agrarian Party
Publishes a monograph, A Political and Economic Democracy, which is adopted as the platform of the Serbian Agrarian Party
Editor-in-Chief, Politika (Belgrade)
Because of pressures on Politika exerted by the personal regime of King Aleksandar, is forced to leave the paper
Plays major part in negotiating an agreement between Croat leader Dr. Maček and Serbian opposition parties
President, Serbian Agrarian Party
Royal Envoy of Yugoslavia to the Soviet Union
Minister (without portfolio) in the General Simović Government
Minister of Justice in the Yugoslav Government in Exile, London

eventgrp.event: President of the Serbian National Federation and the Serbian National Defense. Executive member of the International Peasant Union. Publishes many articles on Communism in English and Serbian, two of which are entered into the Congressional Record ("What Now?" House, 1956, pp. A1741-2; "Street Mobs and Soviet Foreign Policy," Senate, 1960, pp. 15421-2). Resigns from all official positions after his eightieth birthday in 1962, but remains active until shortly before his death, writing monographs and articles and maintaining a voluminous correspondence

chronitem.event: Dies, Bethesda, Maryland, and is buried in the Serbian Orthodox Monastery of Saint Sava in Libertyville near Chicago, Illinois
